---
Title: Enhanced Lists
---

# Enhanced lists

Standard Markdown gives you exactly two kinds of list: unordered lists
(introduced by `-`, `+`, or `*`) and ordered lists numbered with Arabic digits
(`1.`, `2.`, …). That is enough for a shopping list, but it is not enough for the
kind of structured prose that JMarkdown is built for. Legal and academic writing
routinely labels items with letters (`(a)`, `(b)`) or roman numerals (`i`, `ii`,
`iii`); outlines mix all three across nesting levels; and sometimes you need a
list to *start* at a value other than one, or to *skip* a value.

JMarkdown supplies all of this through the **`marked-more-lists`** extension,
which is registered automatically — there is nothing to load or configure. It
teaches the parser to recognise four extra families of list marker and to emit
the corresponding HTML `<ol>` `type` and `<li value="…">` attributes. Ordinary
unordered lists and Arabic ordered lists keep working exactly as before; this
page is about everything beyond them. (For `term : definition` lists, which are a
separate feature, see [Description Lists](description-lists.html).)

## The list markers

An ordered-list item begins with a *counter* — a digit, a letter, or a roman
numeral — followed by a delimiter, either a full stop or a closing parenthesis.
Both delimiters are accepted everywhere a counter is, so `a.` and `a)` are
equivalent ways to start an alphabetic list.

| Marker family | Example | Rendered as | HTML `type` |
|---|---|---|---|
| Arabic numerals | `1.` `2.` | 1, 2, 3 … | (none — the default) |
| Lower-case letters | `a.` `b.` | a, b, c … | `type="a"` |
| Upper-case letters | `A.` `B.` | A, B, C … | `type="A"` |
| Lower-case roman | `i.` `ii.` | i, ii, iii … | `type="i"` |
| Upper-case roman | `I.` `II.` | I, II, III … | `type="I"` |

The counter style is decided by the **first item** of the list. Every following
item is matched against that same style, so a list that opens with `a.` continues
as an alphabetic list and a stray `1.` further down would begin a new list rather
than join the alphabetic one.

### Alphabetic lists

:::markdown-demo
a. First, gather your ingredients.
b. Then prepare the workspace.
c. Finally, begin.
:::

Upper-case letters work the same way and render with `type="A"`:

:::markdown-demo
A. Major premise.
B. Minor premise.
C. Conclusion.
:::

### Roman-numeral lists

Lower-case and upper-case roman numerals are both recognised, and the extension
understands roman arithmetic — `iv` is four, `ix` is nine — so a list may even
begin partway through the sequence (see *Starting value*, below).

:::markdown-demo
i. Introduction
ii. Method
iii. Results
iv. Discussion
:::

### Either delimiter

A closing parenthesis is interchangeable with a full stop, which is handy when
you prefer the `a)` outline convention:

:::markdown-demo
a) one
b) two
c) three
:::

## Nesting and mixing styles

The real power of enhanced lists shows up when you build an outline. Each nesting
level chooses its own counter style, and JMarkdown emits a properly nested set of
`<ol>` elements with the right `type` on each. Indent a sublist beneath its
parent item — the indentation, not the marker, is what creates the nesting.

:::markdown-demo
1. Top-level item
2. Another top-level item
    a. A lettered sub-item
        I. A roman sub-sub-item
        II. Another roman sub-sub-item
    b. Back to letters
3. And back to the top
:::

There is no fixed limit on depth, and no requirement that sibling levels share a
style: the classic legal-outline pattern — numbers, then letters, then lower
roman — is just three indented levels with three different markers.

## Starting value and skipped values

Because the extension reads the *value* of each marker, an ordered list need not
start at one. Begin with whatever counter you like and JMarkdown records the
start by emitting a `value` attribute on the first item:

:::markdown-demo
5. Item five
6. Item six
7. Item seven
:::

The same mechanism lets you **skip** values deliberately. If a marker jumps ahead
of where the automatic count expects, the item carries an explicit `value` so the
visible label matches what you wrote:

:::markdown-demo
1. First
2. Second
9. Jumps to nine
10. and continues from there
:::

This works for letters and roman numerals too — `e.` after `a.` produces an item
with `value="5"`, displayed as *e*.

## Task (checkbox) lists

Enhanced lists also include GitHub-style task lists. Mark an item with `[ ]` for
unchecked or `[x]` (or `[X]`) for checked, immediately after the bullet:

```markdown
- [x] Draft the chapter
- [ ] Revise the chapter
- [ ] Submit the chapter
```

Each item renders as a real, disabled checkbox input. By default the checkbox
sits *after* the list's bullet, which looks doubled-up. The usual remedy is a
small stylesheet that hides the native marker on any list item whose first child
is a checkbox and pulls the row back into alignment:

:::markdown-demo{type=html}
<style>
li:has(input[type="checkbox"]:first-child) {
    list-style: none;
    margin-left: -18pt;
}
</style>

- [x] Draft the chapter
- [ ] Revise the chapter
- [ ] Submit the chapter
:::

The `{type=html}` on the demo above is needed because its source contains a raw
style element; see [Markdown Demo](markdown-demo.html) for that distinction. In a
real document you would normally put the rule once in your stylesheet or
[output template](output-templates.html) rather than inline.

## Gotchas

### Letters that are also roman digits

Seven letters double as roman numerals: **i, v, x, l, c, d, m**. When a list
*starts* with one of these, JMarkdown reads it as a roman numeral, not as an
alphabetic counter, because roman numerals are the more specific interpretation.
So a list opening with `i.` is roman (i, ii, iii …), and a list opening with `c.`
is read as roman *one hundred* — almost certainly not what you meant if you were
trying to label items c, d, e.

If you genuinely want an alphabetic list that happens to begin at one of those
letters, the cleanest fix is to start it earlier (at `a.`) and let it count up,
or to label the items by hand with the `value` you want and the surrounding
prose. Letters with no roman meaning — such as `a`, `b`, `e`, `g` — are
unambiguous and always read as alphabetic.

### Markers do not change `<li>` content

These markers control the list's *numbering*, nothing else. The body of each item
is ordinary markdown: emphasis, links, math, nested blocks, and even further
lists all work inside an item exactly as they do anywhere else.

### LaTeX output is plain `enumerate`

The `marked-more-lists` styling is an HTML feature. In LaTeX mode (`--to latex`)
every ordered list — Arabic, lettered, or roman — is emitted as a standard
`enumerate` environment with plain `\item`s; the `type` and `value` markers are
**not** carried across. If you need lettered or roman enumeration in the print
build, set it in your LaTeX preamble (for example with the `enumitem` package's
`[label=\alph*.]` or `[label=\roman*.]`) so the look is controlled there rather
than in the source.

## Reference

### Markers

| Source marker | List style | HTML attribute on `<ol>` |
|---|---|---|
| `1.` / `1)` | Arabic | none (default) |
| `a.` / `a)` | lower-case letters | `type="a"` |
| `A.` / `A)` | upper-case letters | `type="A"` |
| `i.` / `i)` | lower-case roman | `type="i"` |
| `I.` / `I)` | upper-case roman | `type="I"` |
| `- ` / `+ ` / `* ` | unordered | `<ul>` (no `type`) |

### Item attributes

| Situation | Effect on the item |
|---|---|
| First marker is not the natural start (e.g. `5.`) | `<li value="5">` |
| A marker skips ahead of the running count | `<li value="N">` with the new value |
| `[ ]` after the bullet | disabled, unchecked checkbox |
| `[x]` or `[X]` after the bullet | disabled, checked checkbox |

